But although this assurance derived great authenticity from the number of witnesses by whom it was usually attested, aud from the solemn and public manner in which livery oi seisin was formally given, yet still it may be supposed that inconveniences would frequently arise, either from the loss of the charter itself, or from the difficulty of proving it after a lapse of years. These circumstances probably induced men to look out for some other species of assurance which should be more solemn, more lasting, and more easy to be proved than a charter of feoffment.
